Pretty bad gender ratio in the department (75% male, 25% female). I haven't experienced any worse sexism in the CS department than I normally do everyday as a woman — which isn't saying much lol.
Classes start out freshman year at around 130 to 140 kids in CS 312, the intro CS class. That drops down to around 80 to 100 by the end of CS 314 from my personal experience, though I don't know how much of that is kids dropping or more lecture times.
Any core CS course is going to be taught by professors. The competitiveness depends on the structure of the class — 312 and 314 felt more competitive, but other courses like 429 and 439 (Comp Architecture and OS) are more group project based so there is less of that. Freshman classes are more competitive in general due to imposter syndrome.
For your first year, all core CS courses are usually taught by a single professor (Chand for 312, Scott for 314, Parikh for 311), so scheduling is not as big of an issue. Your pods can also help facilitate this.
Only other advice I could offer: if you do pick UT CS, watch out for imposter syndrome. It is very easy to develop given how big the program is and how many really smart peers you will have. UT CS is a difficult program, but you really learn a lot if you put yourself into it.

